# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: annunciator-panel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:annunciator-panel/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:annunciator-panel/acronyms-and-abbreviations-in-avionics-p01] Below are abbreviations used in aviation, avionics, aerospace, and aeronautics.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] An **adaptive compliant wing** is a wing which is flexible enough for aspects of its shape to be changed in flight.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] Flexible wings have a number of benefits.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] Conventional flight control mechanisms operate using hinges, resulting in disruptions to the airflow, vortices, and in some cases, separation of the airflow.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] These effects contribute to the drag of the aircraft, resulting in less efficiency and higher fuel costs.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] Flexible aerofoils can manipulate aerodynamic forces with less disruptions to the flow, resulting in less aerodynamic drag and improved fuel economy.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] Changing the shape of an aerodynamic surface has a direct effect on its aerodynamic properties.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] According to the flow condition and to the initial shape of the part, each shape variation (curvature, incidence, twist...) can have a different impact on the resulting forces and moments.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] This characteristic is actively pursued in adaptive wings which – by nature of their distributed compliance – can attain shape changes in a continuous, smooth, gap-free manner.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] By altering these geometrical parameters, the forces and moments can be modified, permitting to tailor them to the specific flight condition (e.g. for drag reduction) or to perform maneuvers (e.g. roll).
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] Shape adaptation can be classified according to the motion it enables.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] Changes of the airfoil shapes include altering its twist, and changing its camber and thickness distribution.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] An adaptive compliant wing designed by FlexSys Inc. features a variable-camber trailing edge which can be deflected up to ±10°, thus acting like a flap-equipped wing, but without the individual segments and gaps typical in a flap system.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] The wing itself can be twisted up to 1° per foot of span.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] The wing's shape can be changed at a rate of 30° per second, which is ideal for gust load alleviation.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] The development of the adaptive compliant wing is being sponsored by the U.S.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] Initially, the wing was tested in a wind tunnel, and then a 50-inch (1.3 m) section of wing was flight tested on board the Scaled Composites White Knight research aircraft in a seven-flight, 20-hour program operated from the Mojave Spaceport.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] Adaptive compliant wings are also investigated at ETH Zurich in the frame of the Smart airfoil project.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] The EU-funded Flexop program aims to develop to enable higher wing aspect ratio for less induced drag with lighter, more flexible airliner wings, along developing active flutter suppression for flexible wings.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] Partners include Hungary's MTA SZTAKI, Airbus, Austria's FACC, Inasco of Greece, Delft University of Technology, German aerospace center DLR, TUM, the UK's University of Bristol and RWTH Aachen University in Germany.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] On 19 November 2019, a 7 m (23 ft) span jet-powered UAV demonstrator with an aeroelastically tailored wing for passive load alleviation was flown in Oberpfaffenhofen, Germany, previously flown with a carbon-fiber, rigid wing to establish baseline performance.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] It has a conventional tube-and-wing configuration, unlike the blended wing body of the Lockheed Martin X-56.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] It follows the Grumman X-29 demonstrator in 1984, with more refined fiber orientations.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] The flexible wing is 4% lighter than the rigid one.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] The 54-month, €6.67 million ($7.4 million) project ends in November 2019, followed by the €3.85 million FLiPASED program from September 2019 until December 2022, using all the movable surfaces.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] The glass fiber flutter wing should to be flown in 2020, with unstable aeroelastic modes under 55 m/s (107 kn) that must be actively suppressed.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] With optimized aeroelastic tailoring and active flutter suppression, an aspect ratio of 12.4 could reduce fuel-burn by 5%, and 7% are targeted.
[src:annunciator-panel/adaptive-compliant-wing] FLiPASED is also led by MTA SZTAKI and include partners TUM, DLR and French aerospace research agency ONERA.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Modern aerodynamics only dates back to the seventeenth century, but aerodynamic forces have been harnessed by humans for thousands of years in sailboats and windmills, and images and stories of flight appear throughout recorded history including the Ancient Greek legend of Icarus and Daedalus.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Fundamental concepts of continuum, drag, and pressure gradients appear in the work of Aristotle and Archimedes.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In 1726, Sir Isaac Newton became the first person to develop a theory of air resistance, making him one of the first aerodynamicists.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Dutch-Swiss mathematician Daniel Bernoulli followed in 1738 with *Hydrodynamica* in which he described a fundamental relationship between pressure, density, and flow velocity for incompressible flow known today as Bernoulli's principle, which provides one method for calculating aerodynamic lift.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In 1757, Leonhard Euler published the more general Euler equations which could be applied to both compressible and incompressible flows.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The Euler equations were extended to incorporate the effects of viscosity in the first half of the 1800s, resulting in the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The Navier–Stokes equations are the most general governing equations of fluid flow but are difficult to solve for the flow around all but the simplest of shapes.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In 1799, Sir George Cayley became the first person to identify the four aerodynamic forces of flight (weight, lift, drag, and thrust), as well as the relationships between them, and in doing so outlined the path toward achieving heavier-than-air flight for the next century.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In 1871, Francis Herbert Wenham constructed the first wind tunnel, allowing precise measurements of aerodynamic forces.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Drag theories were developed by Jean Le Rond d'Alembert, Gustav Kirchhoff, and Lord Rayleigh.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In 1889, Charles Renard, a French aeronautical engineer, became the first person to reasonably predict the power needed for sustained flight.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Otto Lilienthal, the first person to become highly successful with glider flights, was also the first to propose thin, curved airfoils that would produce high lift and low drag.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Building on these developments as well as research carried out in their own wind tunnel, the Wright brothers flew the first powered airplane on December 17, 1903.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] During the time of the first flights, Frederick W.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Lanchester, Martin Kutta, and Nikolai Zhukovsky independently created theories which connected circulation of a fluid flow to lift.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Kutta and Zhukovsky then developed a two-dimensional wing theory.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Expanding upon the work of Lanchester, Ludwig Prandtl is credited with developing the mathematics behind thin-airfoil and lifting-line theories as well as working with boundary layers.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] As aircraft speed increased designers began to encounter challenges associated with air compressibility at speeds near the speed of sound.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The differences in airflow under such conditions lead to problems in aircraft control, increased drag due to shock waves and the threat of structural failure due to aeroelastic flutter.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The ratio of the flow speed to the speed of sound was named the Mach number after Ernst Mach who was one of the first to investigate the properties of the supersonic flow.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Macquorn Rankine and Pierre Henri Hugoniot independently developed the theory for flow properties before and after a shock wave, while Jakob Ackeret led the initial work of calculating the lift and drag of supersonic airfoils.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Theodore von Kármán and Hugh Latimer Dryden introduced the term transonic to describe flow speeds between the critical Mach number and Mach 1 where drag increases rapidly.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The rapid increase in drag led aerodynamicists and aviators to disagree on whether supersonic flight was achievable until the sound barrier was broken in 1947 using the Bell X-1 aircraft.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] By the time the sound barrier was broken, aerodynamicists' understanding of the subsonic and low supersonic flow had matured.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The Cold War prompted the design of an ever-evolving line of high-performance aircraft.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Computational fluid dynamics began as an effort to solve for flow properties around complex objects and has rapidly grown to the point where entire aircraft can be designed using computer software, with wind-tunnel tests followed by flight tests to confirm the computer predictions.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Understanding of supersonic and hypersonic aerodynamics has matured since the 1960s, and the goals of aerodynamicists have shifted from the behaviour of fluid flow to the engineering of a vehicle such that it interacts predictably with the fluid flow.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Understanding the motion of air around an object (often called a flow field) enables the calculation of forces and moments acting on the object.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In many aerodynamics problems, the forces of interest are the fundamental forces of flight: lift, drag, thrust, and weight.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Of these, lift and drag are aerodynamic forces, i.e. forces due to air flow over a solid body.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Calculation of these quantities is often founded upon the assumption that the flow field behaves as a continuum.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Continuum flow fields are characterized by properties such as flow velocity, pressure, density, and temperature, which may be functions of position and time.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] These properties may be directly or indirectly measured in aerodynamics experiments or calculated starting with the equations for conservation of mass, momentum, and energy in air flows.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Density, flow velocity, and an additional property, viscosity, are used to classify flow fields.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Flow velocity is used to classify flows according to speed regime.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are flow fields in which the air speed field is always below the local speed of sound.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Transonic flows include both regions of subsonic flow and regions in which the local flow speed is greater than the local speed of sound.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Supersonic flows are defined to be flows in which the flow speed is greater than the speed of sound everywhere.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] A fourth classification, hypersonic flow, refers to flows where the flow speed is much greater than the speed of sound.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree on the precise definition of hypersonic flow.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Compressible flow accounts for varying density within the flow.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are often idealized as incompressible, i.e. the density is assumed to be constant.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Transonic and supersonic flows are compressible, and calculations that neglect the changes of density in these flow fields will yield inaccurate results.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Viscosity is associated with the frictional forces in a flow.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In some flow fields, viscous effects are very small, and approximate solutions may safely neglect viscous effects.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] These approximations are called inviscid flows.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity is not neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Finally, aerodynamic problems may also be classified by the flow environment.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] External aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes (e.g. around an airplane wing), while internal aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages inside solid objects (e.g. through a jet engine).
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Unlike liquids and solids, gases are composed of discrete molecules which occupy only a small fraction of the volume filled by the gas.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] On a molecular level, flow fields are made up of the collisions of many individual gas molecules among themselves, and their collisions with solid surfaces.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] However, in most aerodynamics applications, the discrete molecular nature of gases is ignored, and the flow field is assumed to behave as a continuum.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] This assumption allows fluid properties such as density and flow velocity to be defined everywhere within the flow.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The validity of the continuum assumption is dependent on the density of the gas and the application in question.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] For the continuum assumption to be valid, the mean free path length must be much smaller than the length scale of the application in question.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] For example, many aerodynamics applications deal with aircraft flying in atmospheric conditions, where the mean free path length is on the order of micrometers and where the body is orders of magnitude larger.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In these cases, the length scale of the aircraft ranges from a few meters to a few tens of meters, which is much larger than the mean free path length.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] For such applications, the continuum assumption is reasonable.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The continuum assumption is less valid for extremely low-density flows like those encountered by vehicles at very high altitudes (e.g.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] 300,000 ft/90 km) or satellites in Low Earth orbit.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In these cases, statistical mechanics is a more accurate method of solving the problem than is continuum aerodynamics.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The Knudsen number can be used to guide the choice between statistical mechanics and the continuous formulation of aerodynamics.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The assumption of a fluid continuum allows problems in aerodynamics to be solved using fluid dynamics conservation laws.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Together, the equations are known as Navier–Stokes equations, although some authors define the term to only include the momentum equation(s).
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Navier–Stokes equations have no known analytical solution and are solved in modern aerodynamics using computational techniques.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Because computational methods using high speed computers were not historically available and the high computational cost of solving these complex equations now that they are available, simplifications of the Navier–Stokes equations have been and continue to be employed.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Euler equations are a set of similar conservation equations which neglect viscosity and may be used in cases where the effect of viscosity is expected to be small.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Further simplifications lead to Laplace's equation and potential flow theory.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Additionally, Bernoulli's equation is a solution in one dimension to both the momentum and energy conservation equations.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The ideal gas law or another such equation of state is often used in conjunction with these equations to form a determined system which allows the solution for the unknown variables.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems are classified by the flow environment or properties of the flow, including flow speed, compressibility, and viscosity.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] *External* aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Evaluating the lift and drag on an airplane or the shock waves that form in front of the nose of a rocket are examples of external aerodynamics.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] *Internal* aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages in solid objects.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] For instance, internal aerodynamics encompasses the study of the airflow through a jet engine or through an air conditioning pipe.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems can also be classified according to whether the flow speed is below, near or above the speed of sound.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree over the precise definition of hypersonic flow; a rough definition considers flows with Mach numbers above 5 to be hypersonic.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The influence of viscosity on the flow dictates a third classification.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Some problems may encounter only very small viscous effects, in that case viscosity can be considered to be negligible.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The approximations to these problems are called inviscid flows.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity cannot be neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] An incompressible flow is a flow in which density is constant in both time and space.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Although all real fluids are compressible, a flow is often approximated as incompressible if the effect of the density changes cause only small changes to the calculated results.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] This is more likely to be true when the flow speeds are significantly lower than the speed of sound.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Effects of compressibility are more significant at speeds close to or above the speed of sound.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The Mach number is used to evaluate whether the incompressibility can be assumed, otherwise the effects of compressibility must be included.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Subsonic (or low-speed) aerodynamics describes fluid motion in flows which are much lower than the speed of sound everywhere in the flow.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] There are several branches of subsonic flow but one special case arises when the flow is inviscid, incompressible and irrotational.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] This case is called potential flow and allows the differential equations which describe the flow to be a simplified version of the equations of fluid dynamics, thus making available to the aerodynamicist a range of quick and easy solutions.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In solving a subsonic problem, one decision to be made by the aerodynamicist is whether to incorporate the effects of compressibility.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Compressibility is a description of the amount of change of density in the flow.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] When the effects of compressibility on the solution are small, the assumption that density is constant may be made.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The problem is then an incompressible low-speed aerodynamics problem.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] When the density is allowed to vary, the flow is called compressible.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In air, compressibility effects are usually ignored when the Mach number in the flow does not exceed 0.3 (about 335 feet (102 m) per second or 228 miles (366 km) per hour at 60 °F (16 °C)).
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Above Mach 0.3, the problem flow should be described using compressible aerodynamics.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] According to the theory of aerodynamics, a flow is considered to be compressible if the density changes along a streamline.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] This means that–unlike incompressible flow–changes in density are considered.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In general, this is the case where the Mach number in part or all of the flow exceeds 0.3.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The Mach 0.3 value is rather arbitrary, but it is used because gas flows with a Mach number below that value demonstrate changes in density of less than 5%.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Furthermore, that maximum 5% density change occurs at the stagnation point (the point on the object where flow speed is zero), while the density changes around the rest of the object will be significantly lower.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Transonic, supersonic, and hypersonic flows are all compressible flows.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The term Transonic refers to a range of flow velocities just below and above the local speed of sound (generally taken as Mach 0.8–1.2).
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] It is defined as the range of speeds between the critical Mach number, when some parts of the airflow over an aircraft become supersonic, and a higher speed, typically near Mach 1.2, when all of the airflow is supersonic.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Between these speeds, some of the airflow is supersonic, while some of the airflow is not supersonic.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Supersonic aerodynamic problems are those involving flow speeds greater than the speed of sound.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Calculating the lift on the Concorde during cruise can be an example of a supersonic aerodynamic problem.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Supersonic flow behaves very differently from subsonic flow.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Fluids react to differences in pressure; pressure changes are how a fluid is "told" to respond to its environment.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Therefore, since sound is in fact, an infinitesimal pressure difference propagating through a fluid, the speed of sound in that fluid can be considered the fastest speed that "information" can travel in the flow.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] This difference most obviously manifests itself in the case of a fluid striking an object.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In front of that object, the fluid builds up a stagnation pressure as impact with the object brings the moving fluid to rest.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In fluid traveling at subsonic speed, this pressure disturbance can propagate upstream, changing the flow pattern ahead of the object and giving the impression that the fluid "knows" the object is there by seemingly adjusting its movement and is flowing around it.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In a supersonic flow, however, the pressure disturbance cannot propagate upstream.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Thus, when the fluid finally reaches the object it strikes it and the fluid is forced to change its properties – temperature, density, pressure, and Mach number—in an extremely violent and irreversible fashion called a shock wave.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The presence of shock waves, along with the compressibility effects of high-flow velocity (see Reynolds number) fluids, is the central difference between the supersonic and subsonic aerodynamics regimes.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, hypersonic speeds are speeds that are highly supersonic.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In the 1970s, the term generally came to refer to speeds of Mach 5 (5 times the speed of sound) and above.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The hypersonic regime is a subset of the supersonic regime.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Hypersonic flow is characterized by high temperature flow behind a shock wave, viscous interaction, and chemical dissociation of gas.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The incompressible and compressible flow regimes produce many associated phenomena, such as boundary layers and turbulence.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The concept of a boundary layer is important in many problems in aerodynamics.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The viscosity and fluid friction in the air is approximated as being significant only in this thin layer.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] This assumption makes the description of such aerodynamics much more tractable mathematically.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, turbulence is characterized by chaotic property changes in the flow.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] These include low momentum diffusion, high momentum convection, and rapid variation of pressure and flow velocity in space and time.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Flow that is not turbulent is called laminar flow.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is a significant element of vehicle design, including road cars and trucks where the main goal is to reduce the vehicle drag coefficient, and racing cars, where in addition to reducing drag the goal is also to increase the overall level of downforce.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is also important in the prediction of forces and moments acting on sailing vessels.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] It is used in the design of mechanical components such as hard drive heads.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Structural engineers resort to aerodynamics, and particularly aeroelasticity, when calculating wind loads in the design of large buildings, bridges, and wind turbines.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The aerodynamics of internal passages is important in heating/ventilation, gas piping, and in automotive engines where detailed flow patterns strongly affect the performance of the engine.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Urban aerodynamics are studied by town planners and designers seeking to improve amenity in outdoor spaces, or in creating urban microclimates to reduce the effects of urban pollution.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] The field of environmental aerodynamics describes ways in which atmospheric circulation and flight mechanics affect ecosystems.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic equations are used in numerical weather prediction.
[src:annunciator-panel/aerodynamics] Sports in which aerodynamics are of crucial importance include soccer, table tennis, cricket, baseball, and golf, in which most players can control the trajectory of the ball using the "Magnus effect".
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The **aft pressure bulkhead** or **rear pressure bulkhead** is the rear component of the pressure seal in all aircraft that cruise in a tropopause zone in the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] It helps maintain pressure when stratocruising and protects the aircraft from bursting due to the higher internal pressure.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Aft pressure bulkheads can either be curved, which reduces the amount of metal needed at the cost of reducing the usable space in the airliner, or flat, which gives more internal space but also more weight.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Patents have been filed that propose deliberately creating cavities within the rear bulkhead with the purpose of providing more usable cabin space.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] On several airliners, production of the rear pressure bulkhead has been outsourced to third party manufacturers.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] While typically being a time-consuming and somewhat uncommon process, an aircraft's aft pressure bulkhead can be wholly replaced.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During the twenty-first century, various parties became increasingly interested in developing aft pressure bulkheads composed from composite materials, seeking benefits such as lower manufacturing costs, easier sealing, elimination of corrosion risk, along with weight and part count reductions.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During the early 2000s, Airbus Group developed the largest manufactured resin film infusion structure then in production to function as the aft pressure bulkhead for their double-decker A380 airliner.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Multiple instances of damage to the aft pressure bulkhead have occurred; while a few cases have led to serious failures leading to aircraft losses, others have proven to be survivable.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Aviation certifying authorities have often mandated inspections of an aircraft's aft pressure bulkhead in the interest of safety.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Various techniques have been devised to determine the integrity of the rear pressure bulkhead; these have been used not only to inspect in-service examples but also in the design process, helping to design efficient bulkheads that possess sufficient strength to ensure a safe operational life.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] In 1971, British European Airways Flight 706 crashed in Belgium, killing all 63 on board; the cause was determined to be corrosion of the rear pressure bulkhead by fluid contamination, perhaps from the lavatory.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The corrosion was not detectable by the inspection techniques at the time.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] In 1985, Japan Air Lines Flight 123 crashed after a catastrophic failure of the aft pressure bulkhead.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The failure occurred due to faulty repair of the bulkhead after a tailstrike seven years earlier, when a single repair patch plate was incorrectly cut in two "to make it fit".
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Failure of the bulkhead damaged hydraulic pipes passing through.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Boeing later calculated that the incorrect installation would be expected to fail after approximately 10,000 pressurizations; the repaired aircraft accomplished 12,318 successful flights before the crash.
[src:annunciator-panel/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During 2013, National Airlines Flight 102 crashed after loose freight on the main deck is believed to have penetrated the aft pressure bulkhead and caused damage to control systems in the vicinity of the bulkhead.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:annunciator-panel/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] An **aileron** (French for 'little wing' or 'fin') is a hinged flight control surface usually forming part of the trailing edge of each wing of a fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Ailerons are used in pairs to control the aircraft in roll (or movement around the aircraft's longitudinal axis), which normally results in a change in flight path due to the tilting of the lift vector.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Movement around this axis is called rolling or banking.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Considerable controversy exists over credit for the invention of the aileron.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The Wright brothers and Glenn Curtiss fought a years-long legal battle over the Wright patent of 1906, which described a method of wing-warping to achieve lateral control.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The brothers prevailed in several court decisions which found that Curtiss's use of ailerons violated the Wright patent.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Ultimately, the First World War compelled the U.S.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Government to legislate a legal resolution.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] A much earlier aileron concept was patented in 1868 by British scientist Matthew Piers Watt Boulton, based on his 1864 paper *On Aërial Locomotion*.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The name "aileron", from French, meaning "little wing", also refers to the extremities of a bird's wings used to control their flight.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] It first appeared in print in the 7th edition of Cassell's French-English Dictionary of 1877, with its lead meaning of "small wing".
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] In the context of powered airplanes it appears in print about 1908.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Prior to that, ailerons were often referred to as rudders, their older technical sibling, with no distinction between their orientations and functions, or more descriptively as *horizontal rudders* (in French, *gouvernails horizontaux*).
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Among the earliest printed aeronautical use of 'aileron' was that in the French aviation journal *L'Aérophile* of 1908.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Ailerons had more or less completely supplanted other forms of lateral control, such as wing warping, by about 1915, well after the function of the rudder and elevator flight controls had been largely standardised.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] He was the first to patent an aileron control system in 1868.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Boulton's description of his lateral flight control system was "the first record we have of appreciation of the necessity for active lateral control as distinguished from [passive lateral stability]....
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] With this invention of Boulton's we have the birth of the present-day three torque method of airborne control" as was praised by Charles Manly.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] 392 of 1868, issued about 35 years before ailerons were "reinvented" in France, became forgotten and lost from sight until after the flight control device was in general use.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Gibbs-Smith stated on several occasions that if the Boulton patent had been revealed at the time of the Wright brothers' legal filings, they might not have been able to claim priority of invention for the lateral control of flying machines.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The fact that the Wright brothers were able to gain a patent in 1906 did not invalidate Boulton's lost and forgotten invention.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The pioneering U.S. aeronautical engineer Octave Chanute published descriptions and drawings of the Wright brothers' 1902 glider in the leading aviation periodical of the day, *L'Aérophile*, in 1903.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] This prompted Esnault-Pelterie, a French military engineer, to build a Wright-style glider in 1904 that used ailerons in lieu of wing warping.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The French journal *L'Aérophile* then published photos of the ailerons on Esnault-Pelterie's glider which were included in his June 1905 article, and its ailerons were widely copied afterward.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The Wright brothers used wing warping instead of ailerons for roll control on their glider in 1902, and about 1904 their Flyer II was the only aircraft of its time able to do a coordinated banked turn.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] During the early years of powered flight the Wrights had better roll control on their designs than airplanes that used movable surfaces.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] From 1908, as aileron designs were refined it became clear that ailerons were much more effective and practical than wing warping.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Ailerons also had the advantage of not weakening the airplane's wing structure as did the wing warping technique, which was one reason for Esnault-Pelterie's decision to switch to ailerons.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] By 1911, most biplanes used ailerons rather than wing warping—by 1915, ailerons had become almost universal on monoplanes as well.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Government, frustrated by the lack of its country's aeronautical advances in the years leading up to World War I, enforced a patent pool effectively putting an end to the Wright brothers patent war.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The Wright company quietly changed its aircraft flight controls from wing warping to the use of ailerons at that time as well.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The Wright Brothers' Ohio patent attorney Henry Toulmin filed an expansive patent application and on May 22, 1906, the brothers were granted U.S.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The patent's importance lay in its claim of a new and useful method of *controlling* an airplane.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The patent application included the claim for the lateral control of aircraft flight that was not limited to wing warping, but through any manipulation of the "....angular relations of the lateral margins of the airplanes [wings].... varied in opposite directions".
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Thus the patent explicitly stated that other methods besides wing-warping could be used for adjusting the outer portions of an airplane's wings to different angles on its right and left sides to achieve lateral roll control.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Patent 831173 at nearly the same time for his methods of wing warping.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Both the Wright Brothers patent and Montgomery's patent were reviewed and approved by the same patent examiner at the United States Patent Office, William Townsend.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] At the time Townsend indicated that both methods of wing warping were invented independently and were sufficiently different to each justify their own patent award.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Multiple U.S. court decisions favoured the expansive Wright patent, which the Wright Brothers sought to enforce with licensing fees starting from $1,000 per airplane, and said to range up to $1,000 per day.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Casey, a former curator of the Smithsonian Air & Space Museum in Washington, D.C., and other researchers, due to the patent they had received the Wrights stood firmly on the position that all flying using lateral roll control, anywhere in the world, would only be conducted under license by them.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Years of protracted legal conflict ensued with many other aircraft builders until the U.S. entered World War I, when the government imposed a legislated agreement among the parties which resulted in royalty payments of 1% to the Wrights.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] There are still conflicting claims today over who first invented the aileron.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Other 19th century engineers and scientists, including Charles Renard, Alphonse Pénaud, and Louis Mouillard, had described similar flight control surfaces.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Another technique for lateral flight control, wing warping, was also described or experimented with by several people including Jean-Marie Le Bris, John Montgomery, Clement Ader, Edson Gallaudet, D.D.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Gibbs-Smith wrote that the aileron was "....one of the most remarkable inventions... of aeronautical history, which was immediately lost sight of".
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Ailerons are usually situated near the wing tip, but may sometimes also be situated nearer the wing root.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Modern airliners may also have a second pair of ailerons on their wings, with the two positions distinguished by the terms "outboard aileron" and "inboard aileron".
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] An unwanted side effect of aileron operation is adverse yaw, a yawing moment in the opposite direction to the roll.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Using the ailerons to roll an aircraft to the right produces a yawing motion to the left.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] As the aircraft rolls, adverse yaw is caused partly by the change in drag between the left and right wing.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The rising wing generates increased lift, which causes increased induced drag.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The descending wing generates reduced lift, which causes reduced induced drag.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Profile drag caused by the deflected ailerons may add further to the difference, along with changes in the lift vectors as one rotates back while the other rotates forward.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] In a coordinated turn, adverse yaw is effectively compensated by the use of the rudder, which results in a sideforce on the vertical tail that opposes the adverse yaw by creating a favorable yawing moment.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Another method of compensation is "differential ailerons", which have been rigged so that the down-going aileron deflects less than the up-going one.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] In this case the opposing yaw moment is generated by a difference in profile drag between the left and right wingtips.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Ailerons may also be designed to use a combination of these methods.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] With ailerons in the neutral position, the wing on the outside of the turn develops more lift than the opposite wing due to the variation in airspeed across the wing span, which tends to cause the aircraft to continue to roll.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Once the desired angle of bank (degree of rotation about the longitudinal axis) has been obtained, the pilot uses opposite aileron to prevent the angle of bank from increasing due to this variation in lift across the wing span.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] This minor opposite use of the control must be maintained throughout the turn.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The pilot also uses a slight amount of rudder in the same direction as the turn to counteract adverse yaw and to produce a "coordinated" turn wherein the fuselage is parallel to the flight path.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] A simple gauge on the instrument panel called the slip indicator, also known as "the ball", indicates when this coordination is achieved.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Particularly on larger or faster aircraft, control forces may be extremely heavy.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Borrowing a discovery from boats that extending a control surface's area forward of the hinge lightens the forces needed first appeared on ailerons during World War I when ailerons were extended beyond the wingtip and provided with a horn ahead of the hinge.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Known as overhung ailerons, possibly the best known examples are the Handley Page Type O (first flight 17 December 1915), Sopwith Snipe, Fokker Dr.I and Fokker D.VII.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Later examples brought the counterbalance in line with the wing to improve control and reduce drag.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] This is seen less often now, due to the Frise type aileron which provides the same benefit.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Trim tabs are small movable sections resembling scaled down ailerons located at or near the trailing edge of the aileron.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] On most propeller powered aircraft, the rotation of the propellers induces a counteracting roll movement due to Newton's third law of motion, in that every action has an equal and opposite reaction.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] To relieve the pilot of having to provide continuous pressure on the stick in one direction, which causes fatigue, trim tabs are provided to adjust or *trim out* the pressure needed against any unwanted movement.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The tab itself is deflected in relation to the aileron, causing the aileron to move in the opposite direction.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Trim tabs come in two forms, adjustable and fixed.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] A fixed trim tab is manually bent to the required amount of deflection, while the adjustable trim tab can be controlled from within the cockpit so that different power settings or flight attitudes can be compensated for.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Some large aircraft from the 1950s (including the Canadair Argus) used free floating control surfaces that the pilot controlled only through the deflection of trim tabs, in which case additional tabs were also provided to fine-tune the control to provide straight and level flight.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Spades are flat metal plates, usually attached to the aileron lower surface, ahead of the aileron hinge, by a lever arm.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] They reduce the force needed by the pilot to deflect the aileron and are often seen on aerobatic aircraft.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] As the aileron is deflected upward, the spade produces a downward aerodynamic force, which tends to rotate the whole assembly so as to further deflect the aileron upward.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The size of the spade (and its lever arm) determines how much force the pilot needs to apply to deflect the aileron.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] A spade works in the same manner as a horn but is more effective due to the longer moment arm.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] To increase the speed at which control surface flutter (aeroelastic flutter) might become a risk, the center of gravity of the control surface is moved towards the hinge-line for that surface.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] To achieve this, lead weights may be added to the front of the aileron.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] In some aircraft the aileron construction may be too heavy to allow this system to work without an excessive increase in the weight of the aileron.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] In this case, the weight may be added to a lever arm to move the weight well out in front to the aileron body.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] These balance weights are tear drop shaped (to reduce drag), which make them appear quite different from spades, although both project forward and below the aileron.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] In addition to reducing the risk of flutter, mass balances also reduce the stick forces required to move the control surface in maneuvers.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Used during aviation's pre-war "pioneer era" and into the early years of the First World War, these ailerons were each controlled by a single cable, which pulled the aileron up.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] When the aircraft was at rest, the ailerons hung vertically down.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] This type of aileron was used on the Farman III biplane 1909 and the Short 166.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] A "reverse" version of this, utilizing wing-warping, existed on the later version of the Santos-Dumont *Demoiselle*, which only warped the wingtips "downward".
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] One of the disadvantages of this setup was a greater tendency to yaw than even with basic interconnected ailerons.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] During the 1930s, a number of light aircraft used single acting controls but used springs to return the ailerons to their neutral positions when the stick was released.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The main problem with this type of aileron is the dangerous tendency to stall if used aggressively, especially if the aircraft is already in danger of stalling, hence the use primarily on prototypes, and their replacement on production aircraft with more conventional ailerons.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Engineer Leslie George Frise (1897–1979) of the Bristol Aeroplane Company developed an aileron shape that is pivoted at about its 25 to 30% chord line and near its bottom surface , in order to decrease stick forces as aircraft became faster during the 1930s.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] When the aileron is deflected up (to make its wing go down), the leading edge of the aileron starts to protrude below the underside of the wing into the airflow beneath the wing.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The moment of the leading edge in the airflow helps to move up the trailing edge, which decreases the stick force.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The down moving aileron also adds energy to the boundary layer.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The edge of the aileron directs air flow from the underside of the wing to the upper surface of the aileron, thus creating a lifting force added to the lift of the wing.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] This reduces the needed deflection of the aileron.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Both the Canadian Fleet Model 2 biplane of 1930 and the 1938 popular US Piper J-3 Cub monoplane possessed Frise ailerons as designed and helped introduce them to a wide audience.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] A claimed benefit of the Frise aileron is the ability to counteract adverse yaw.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] To do so, the leading edge of the aileron has to be sharp or bluntly rounded, which adds significant drag to the upturned aileron and helps counterbalance the yaw force created by the other aileron turned down.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] This can add some unpleasant, nonlinear effect and/or potentially dangerous aerodynamic vibration (flutter).
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Adverse yaw moment is basically countered by aircraft yaw stability and also by the use of differential aileron movement.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The Frise-type aileron also forms a slot, so air flows smoothly over the lowered aileron, making it more effective at high angles of attack.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Frise-type ailerons may also be designed to function differentially.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Like the differential aileron, the Frise-type aileron does not eliminate adverse yaw entirely.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Coordinated rudder application is still needed when ailerons are applied.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] By careful design of the mechanical linkages, the up aileron can be made to deflect more than the down aileron (e.g., US patent 1,565,097).
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] This helps reduce the likelihood of a wing tip stall when aileron deflections are made at high angles of attack.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] In addition, the consequent differential in drag reduces adverse yaw (as also discussed above).
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The idea is that the loss of lift associated with the up aileron carries no penalty while the increase in lift associated with the down aileron is minimized.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The rolling couple on the aircraft is always the difference in lift between the two wings.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] A designer at de Havilland invented a simple and practical linkage and their de Havilland Tiger Moth classic British biplane became one of the best-known aircraft, and one of the earliest, to use differential ailerons.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] On the earliest Pioneer Era aircraft, such as the Wright Flyer and the later, 1909-origin Blériot XI and Etrich Taube, lateral control was effected by twisting the outboard portion of the wing so as to increase or decrease lift by changing the angle of attack.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] This had the disadvantages of stressing the structure, being heavy on the controls, and of risking stalling the side with the increased angle of attack during a maneuver.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] By 1916, most designers had abandoned wing warping in favor of ailerons.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Researchers at NASA and elsewhere have been taking a second look at wing warping again, although under new names.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The NASA version is the X-53 Active Aeroelastic Wing while the United States Air Force tested the Adaptive Compliant Wing.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Spoilers are devices that when extended into the airflow over a wing, disrupt the airflow and reduce the amount of lift generated.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Many modern aircraft designs, especially jet aircraft, use spoilers in lieu of, or to supplement ailerons, such as the F4 Phantom II and Northrop P-61 Black Widow, which had almost full width flaps (there were very small conventional ailerons at the wingtips as well).
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] All aircraft with dihedral have some form of yaw-roll coupling to promote stability.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Common trainers like the Cessna 152/172 series can be roll controlled with rudder alone.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] The rudder of the Boeing 737 has more roll authority over the aircraft than the ailerons at high angles of attack.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] This led to two notable accidents when the rudder jammed in the fully deflected position causing rollovers (see Boeing 737 rudder issues).
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Some aircraft such as the Fokker Spin and model gliders lack any type of lateral control.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Those aircraft use a higher amount of dihedral than conventional aircraft.
[src:annunciator-panel/aileron] Deflecting the rudder gives yaw and a lot of differential wing lift, giving a yaw induced roll moment.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] An **annunciator panel**, also known in some aircraft as the **Centralized Warning Panel** (**CWP**) or **Caution Advisory Panel** (**CAP**), is a group of lights used as a central indicator of the status of equipment or systems in an aircraft, industrial process, building or other installation.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] Usually, the annunciator panel includes a main warning lamp or audible signal to draw the attention of operating personnel to the annunciator panel for abnormal events or conditions.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] In the aircraft industry, annunciator panels are groupings of **annunciator lights** that indicate status of the aircraft's subsystems.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] The lights are usually accompanied with a test switch, which when pressed illuminates all the lights to confirm they are in working order.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] More advanced modern aircraft replaces these with the integrated electronic Engine Indicating and Crew Alerting System or Electronic Centralised Aircraft Monitor.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] An aviation annunciator panel will have a test switch to check for burned out lamps.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] Indicator lights are grouped by their associated systems into various panels of lights.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] More complicated aircraft will feature **Master Warning** and **Master Caution** lights/switches.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] In the event of any red or yellow annunciator being activated, the yellow or red master light, usually located elsewhere in the pilot's line of sight, will illuminate.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] In most installations they will flash and an audible alert will accompany them.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] These "masters" will not stop flashing until they have been acknowledged, usually by pressing the light itself, and in some cases the audible alert will also continue until this acknowledgement.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] On some aircraft (most Boeing airliners, for example) the "masters" will also flash briefly and the audible alert will sound whenever the autopilot is disconnected, as an additional reminder to the pilots that manual control is now required.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] In industrial process control, an annunciator panel is a system to alert operators of alarm conditions in the plant.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] Multiple back-lit windows are provided, each engraved with the name of a process alarm.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] Lamps in each window are controlled by hard-wired switches in the plant, arranged to operate when a process condition enters an abnormal state (such as high temperature, low pressure, loss of cooling water flow, or many others).
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] Single-point or multipoint alarm logic modules operate the window lights based on a preselected ISA 18.1 or custom sequence.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] In one common alarm sequence, the light in a window will flash, and a bell or horn will sound to attract the operator's attention when the alarm condition is detected.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] The operator can silence the alarm with a button, and the window will remain lit as long as the process is in the alarm state.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] When the alarm clears (process condition returns to normal), the lamps in the window go out.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] Annunciator panels were relatively costly to install in a plant because they had dedicated wiring to the alarm-initiating devices in the process plant.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] Since incandescent lamps were used, a lamp test button was always provided to allow early detection of failed lamps.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] Modern electronic distributed control systems usually require less wiring since the process signals can be monitored within the control system, and the engraved windows are replaced by alphanumeric displays on a computer monitor.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] The behavior of alarm systems and colors used to indicate alarms are standardized.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] Standards such as ISA 18.1 or EN 60073 simplify the purchase of systems and the training of operators by giving standard alarm sequences.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] The introduction of computer monitor-based control systems during the 1980s and 1990s saw a wholesale absorption of alarm window displays onto the computer screen.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] This created a downturn in the sales of the conventional alarm annunciator systems, and many of the companies manufacturing these alarm annunciator products were either sold off or went out of business.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] This has left today a major obsolescence support problem for customers who are still using these alarm annunciator systems as part of their safety systems.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] Over the last five years The alarm annunciator has seen a resurgence in popularity, especially for use in IEC 61508 SIL 1 and SHE (Safety Health and Environmental) alarm monitoring applications.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] The modern trend is to identify critical alarms and return them from the computer screen to discrete alarm windows.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] Firstly, alarm annunciators offer pattern recognition to the operators in the form of LED alarm fascias instead of just providing an exhaustive list of alarms and events which the operators have to scroll through and in some instances alarms can be overlooked.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] Secondly, the analysis of plant failure modes is leading to the separation of critical alarm monitoring and process control systems for safety reasons.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] In large buildings, a fire alarm control panel is located in a secure location, such as in an electrical room where it is also convenient for running electrical wires for system components or in a fire command center.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] A fire alarm annunciator panel is located where it is accessible to fire-fighting crews, such as at building entrances/exits.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] The annunciator panel will indicate the system status using lamps (or LEDs), an audible warning tone, and, depending on the system technology, the exact location or approximate physical location of the source of a fire alarm in the building.
[src:annunciator-panel/annunciator-panel] In a large, high-occupancy building such as an office tower or hotel, the fire annunciator may also be associated with a control panel for building ventilation systems, and may also include emergency communication systems for the building.
